#b
mean_male = c()
mean_female =c()
maledata = data[data$V2=="M",]
femaledata = data[data$V2=="F",]
for(i in 1:4){
  mean_male[i] = mean(maledata[,i+2])
  mean_female[i] = mean(femaledata[,i+2])
}

plot(levels(factor(longdata$Ages)),mean_male,col=2,xlab='Ages',ylab='mean growth',xlim=c(8,14),ylim=c(21,29))
lines(levels(factor(longdata$Ages)),mean_male,col=1)
points(levels(factor(longdata$Ages)),mean_female,col=3)
lines(levels(factor(longdata$Ages)),mean_female,col=4)

From the plot, we can tell the growth amount for male id higher than female. And the growth rate for male is also higher than the female after age 10.

#2b

library(nlme)
m1 <- gls(Dental_growth ~ Ages*Gender, data=longdata, 
          corr=corSymm(form= ~  Time | ID), 
          weights=varIdent(form= ~ 1 | Ages))

longdata$agefactor = factor(longdata$Ages)
m2 <- gls(Dental_growth ~ agefactor*Gender, data=longdata, 
          corr=corSymm(form= ~ Time | ID), 
          weights=varIdent(form= ~ 1 | agefactor)) 


longdata$year_10 <- (longdata$Ages-10)*I(longdata$Ages>=10)
m3 <- gls(Dental_growth ~ Ages*Gender+year_10*Gender, data=longdata, 
          corr=corSymm(form= ~ Time | ID),
          weights=varIdent(form= ~ 1 | Ages))


longdata$num_year = longdata$Ages-mean(longdata$Ages)
longdata$num_year2 = (longdata$num_year)^2
### Fit a quadratic trend model
m4 <- gls(Dental_growth ~ Gender*num_year+Gender*num_year2, data=longdata,
          corr=corSymm(form= ~ Time | ID),
          weights=varIdent(form= ~ 1 | Ages))

corandcov2 <- function(glsob,cov=T,...){
  corm <- corMatrix(glsob$modelStruct$corStruct)[[1]]
  corv<-print(getVarCov(glsob))
  return(corm)
  }

t_value <- function(model,cov) {
  a <- as.data.frame(coef(summary(model))[,3:4])
  a$covstr <- cov
  a$effect <- rownames(a)
  a
}

tTable <- rbind(t_value(m1,'IND'),t_value(m2,'UN'),t_value(m3,'CS'),t_value(m4,'AR(1)'),
                t_value(m5,'Toep'),t_value(m6,'Exp'),t_value(m7,'CSH'))

est <- function(model,cov) {
  a <- as.data.frame(intervals(model)$coef)
  a$covstr <- cov
  a$effect <- rownames(a)
  a
}

fixed <- rbind(est(m1,'IND'),est(m2,'UN'),est(m3,'CS'),est(m4,'AR(1)'),
               est(m5,"Toe"),est(m6,'Exp'),est(m7,'CSH'))
fixed1 = fixed[fixed$effect == 'GenderM:agefactor10',]
fixed2 = fixed[fixed$effect == 'GenderM:agefactor12',]
fixed3 = fixed[fixed$effect == 'GenderM:agefactor14',]
fixed = rbind(fixed1,fixed2,fixed3)

library(ggplot2)
p1 <- ggplot(fixed, aes(x=covstr,y=est.))
p1 + facet_wrap(~effect, scales = "free") + geom_point(size=7) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=lower,ymax=upper)) +
  labs(title="Estimates of Fixed Effects with 95% CI Assuming Different Covariance Structures",
       x="Covariance Structure", y="Estimate")

The CI for the IND is the widest. The confidence interval doest not include 0 then it is significant.

The GenderM:agefactor10 coefficient is -0.1079545 which means the interative of GenderM:agefactor10 will decrease when this item increase. Similarly, the agefactor12 coefficient is 1.9090909, which means the agefactor increase 1 the growth will increase 1.9090909. The other will represent the similar meaning in this way.
